1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,419
Jab bhi mai in videos ko bana raha hota hoon, kabhi-kabhi ek special

2
00:00:03,419 --> 00:00:07,090
moment aata hai jab animation banate time choti-choti technical problems

3
00:00:07,090 --> 00:00:10,459
solve karni padti hain, aur phir jo math mai samjhana chahta hoon,

4
00:00:10,459 --> 00:00:14,080
wo ekdum clear ho jaata hai jab mai use screen par live dekh leta hoon.

5
00:00:14,480 --> 00:00:17,420
In moments ke best versions aksar mujhe bata dete hain ki koi

6
00:00:17,420 --> 00:00:20,408
video meri favorites me se ek hone wali hai, aur iss piece ke

7
00:00:20,408 --> 00:00:23,300
end ko assemble karte waqt bhi mujhe wahi feeling aayi thi.

8
00:00:27,040 --> 00:00:30,140
Hamari kahani aaj actually math classroom se start nahi hoti.

9
00:00:30,460 --> 00:00:31,860
Hum art room se shuru karte hain.

10
00:00:32,720 --> 00:00:36,488
Sochein aap ek gallery me hain, harbour me ek boat ki photo dekh rahe hain,

11
00:00:36,488 --> 00:00:39,251
aur jaise hi aapki nazar upar right side me jaati hai,

12
00:00:39,251 --> 00:00:43,120
poori duniya hil jaati hai, wahan aapko waterfront pe ek village dikhta hai.

13
00:00:43,640 --> 00:00:48,106
In buildings ke beech, jaise hi aap neeche ek building ke entrance ki taraf dekhte hain,

14
00:00:48,106 --> 00:00:52,420
duniya aur ajeeb lagne lagti hai, wahan se ek hallway hai jahan pe artwork laga hai.

15
00:00:53,200 --> 00:00:56,880
Aur iss hallway ke end me, wapas aap yahin hain, ek boat ki picture ko dekhte hue.

16
00:00:58,520 --> 00:00:59,860
Yeh hai M.C.

17
00:00:59,980 --> 00:01:05,340
Escher ka 1956 ka lithograph, Print Gallery, ya Dutch me, Prentendentunstelling.

18
00:01:05,960 --> 00:01:08,445
Ek letter mein jo unhone apne beta ko likha tha,

19
00:01:08,445 --> 00:01:12,742
apni ek aisi creation ka zikr kiya jisme ek young man interest se us print ko dekh

20
00:01:12,742 --> 00:01:16,780
raha hai jisme khud artist hi hai, Escher ne ise apni sabse ajeeb cheez kaha,

21
00:01:16,780 --> 00:01:18,540
jo unke liye kaafi badi baat thi.

22
00:01:18,900 --> 00:01:21,718
Escher ki art duniya bhar me kaafi pasand ki jaati hai,

23
00:01:21,718 --> 00:01:26,073
jo aksar paradoxical themes ya kisi character ke saath uniquely satisfying geometric

24
00:01:26,073 --> 00:01:27,200
patterns dikhati hai.

25
00:01:27,500 --> 00:01:30,650
Yeh pyaar especially mathematicians ke beech zyada hai,

26
00:01:30,650 --> 00:01:35,060
kyunki unki art aksar math ke surprisingly deep concepts ko touch karti hai,

27
00:01:35,060 --> 00:01:38,840
jabki Escher khud ne is field me koi formal training nahi li thi.

28
00:01:39,520 --> 00:01:43,380
The Print Gallery is unexpected depth ka ek perfect example hai.

29
00:01:43,380 --> 00:01:46,824
2003 me, mathematicians De Smit aur Lenstra ne is piece ka ek

30
00:01:46,824 --> 00:01:50,211
bahut hi interesting analysis diya tha, aur us mind-bending

31
00:01:50,211 --> 00:01:54,220
self-contained loop ko explain kiya tha jo Escher ne achieve kiya tha.

32
00:01:54,720 --> 00:01:59,114
Is video ke saath mera main goal hai ki mai unke analysis ko visually unpack karu,

33
00:01:59,114 --> 00:02:02,276
hamesha ki tarah yeh feel dene ki koshish karte hue ki aap

34
00:02:02,276 --> 00:02:04,420
khud bhi isse rediscover kar sakte the.

35
00:02:05,120 --> 00:02:08,051
Is analysis se ek cheez jo unexpectedly saamne aati hai,

36
00:02:08,051 --> 00:02:12,080
wo hai is sawal ka jawab ki exactly is picture ke beech me kya hona chahiye.

37
00:02:12,580 --> 00:02:15,240
Shuru me toh yeh ek incoherent question lag sakta hai.

38
00:02:15,600 --> 00:02:19,470
Agar aap upar right se dekhein, toh lagta hai jaise yeh village ki buildings ko feature

39
00:02:19,470 --> 00:02:23,340
kar raha hai, lekin left se dekhein toh yeh zyada picture frame ka hissa lag raha hai.

40
00:02:23,620 --> 00:02:27,740
Lekin agar aap neeche se dekhein, toh yeh khud gallery ka hi part lagta zyada lag rha hai.

41
00:02:28,160 --> 00:02:31,518
Kuch tareeke se is poore scene me aap exactly kahan hain,

42
00:02:31,518 --> 00:02:35,760
uski saari ambiguity us blank circle ke beech me compress ho jaati hai.

43
00:02:36,220 --> 00:02:38,656
Bas maza lene ke liye, kyunki abhi 2020s chal raha hai,

44
00:02:38,656 --> 00:02:40,960
maine ek diffusion model se yeh fill karne ko bola.

45
00:02:41,500 --> 00:02:43,280
Aur use bohot struggle karni padi.

46
00:02:43,860 --> 00:02:45,200
Wo bilkul samajh hi nahi paa rha.

47
00:02:45,740 --> 00:02:48,080
Aur bechari machine ko credit dena chahiye, use mushkil hoti hai.

48
00:02:48,480 --> 00:02:52,320
Ye scene kaafi ambiguous aur sahi tareeke se define nahi lag raha hai.

49
00:02:52,780 --> 00:02:57,152
Lekin fir bhi, end tak mai chahta hu aap agree kare ki ek hi completion

50
00:02:57,152 --> 00:03:01,340
hai jo sahi puzzle piece lagta hai jo aap easily fit kar sakte hai.

51
00:03:02,100 --> 00:03:05,868
Maths me ghusne se pehle, mai aapko ek bilkul intuitive description dena chahta

52
00:03:05,868 --> 00:03:09,780
hu ki Escher ne actually ye piece kaise banaya, jo teen steps me divide hota hai.

53
00:03:10,340 --> 00:03:14,749
Pehla step hai ki isi concept ke ek straightened out version se shuru kare,

54
00:03:14,749 --> 00:03:17,160
jahan ek aadmi ek picture dekh raha hai.

55
00:03:17,640 --> 00:03:22,943
Us picture me ek harbor hai, jisme ek town hai, jisme ek print gallery hai,

56
00:03:22,943 --> 00:03:26,620
jisme wahi aadmi hai, aur aise hi chalta rehta hai.

57
00:03:26,720 --> 00:03:28,820
Aap jitna man chahe utna zoom in kar sakte hai.

58
00:03:30,380 --> 00:03:33,878
Self-similar image ka ye idea, jahan picture khud ke andar hai,

59
00:03:33,878 --> 00:03:36,820
use graphic designers ek special naam se jaante hai.

60
00:03:37,180 --> 00:03:39,561
Ye Drosta effect hai, jo ek cocoa company ke naam

61
00:03:39,561 --> 00:03:42,040
par hai jinhone ise apni branding me use kiya tha.

62
00:03:42,560 --> 00:03:45,386
Actually, yeh ek common marketing gimmick hai jo early 20th

63
00:03:45,386 --> 00:03:48,020
century ke har tarah ke products ke liye use hota tha.

64
00:03:48,480 --> 00:03:52,295
Jo self-similar Drosta image Escher use kar rahe the,

65
00:03:52,295 --> 00:03:55,606
usme zoom in sabse bahut zyada deep hota hai,

66
00:03:55,606 --> 00:04:00,140
jahan self-similar copy original se 256 times chhoti hoti hai.

67
00:04:00,520 --> 00:04:02,420
Aap abhi thodi der me dekh lenge ki yeh number kahan se aaya.

68
00:04:03,160 --> 00:04:08,655
Escher ki genius baat ye thi ki unhone intuitively samjh liya ki picture ko khud me

69
00:04:08,655 --> 00:04:14,216
nest karne ka koi way ho sakta hai aur usko ek aise warped loop me badal diya jahan

70
00:04:14,216 --> 00:04:19,579
zooming automatically hoti hai jab viewer ki nazar circle ke around ghoomti hai.

71
00:04:21,180 --> 00:04:24,714
Waise, aap soch rahe honge ki yeh straightened out version mujhe kahan se mila,

72
00:04:24,714 --> 00:04:27,444
actually woh do mathematicians jinhe maine mention kiya tha,

73
00:04:27,444 --> 00:04:28,920
vo humein use karne de rahe hai.

74
00:04:28,920 --> 00:04:33,080
Ye actually unhone original Escher piece ko reverse engineer karke banaya tha,

75
00:04:33,080 --> 00:04:36,600
do Dutch artists, Hans Richter aur Jacqueline Hofstra ki help se.

76
00:04:37,140 --> 00:04:39,900
Jis tarha unhone isko reverse engineer kiya, voh kaafi interesting hai.

77
00:04:40,280 --> 00:04:44,460
Ek trah se dekha jaye to, ye aisa hai jaise original piece ka logarithm le rahe ho.

78
00:04:44,920 --> 00:04:47,490
Mujhe pata hai abhi ye sentence thoda ajeeb lag raha hoga,

79
00:04:47,490 --> 00:04:51,300
lekin is video ke aage jaake mai promise karta hu ki sab kuch bilkul clear ho jayega.

80
00:04:52,220 --> 00:04:56,094
Escher ne ye loop kaise banaya, iska basic idea samjhane ke liye mai ek aisa

81
00:04:56,094 --> 00:04:58,948
example lena chahta hu jo unke wale se thoda simple ho,

82
00:04:58,948 --> 00:05:02,924
toh hum ye custom self-similar Drosta image dekhte hain jisme ek pie creature

83
00:05:02,924 --> 00:05:07,460
ek framed house ki picture dekh raha hai, aur usi house mein woh pie creature rehta hai.

84
00:05:08,140 --> 00:05:12,250
Is example mein, self-similar copy original se sirf 16 times chhoti hai,

85
00:05:12,250 --> 00:05:15,560
aur isse sab kuch ek saath dekhna kaafi easy ho jata hai.

86
00:05:15,980 --> 00:05:20,581
Ab mai kya karunga ki yahan right side pe ek alag workspace rakhta hu jisme hum

87
00:05:20,581 --> 00:05:25,298
jo general goal hai usko sketch karenge, jahan aap aise soch sakte hain ki aapko

88
00:05:25,298 --> 00:05:29,840
woh 16-fold zoom-in factor square ke chaar corners mein distribute karna hai.

89
00:05:30,560 --> 00:05:33,525
Jaise maan lijiye aap chahte hain ki pie creature khud

90
00:05:33,525 --> 00:05:36,380
almost same size mein lower left corner mein dikhe.

91
00:05:36,880 --> 00:05:40,742
Toh agar aap original image mein 2 ka factor leke zoom in karte hain,

92
00:05:40,742 --> 00:05:43,373
toh jo zoomed version ke upper left mein hoga,

93
00:05:43,373 --> 00:05:46,620
usko hum apne workspace ke upper left mein place karenge.

94
00:05:47,340 --> 00:05:50,537
Usi tarah, phir se 2 ka factor leke zoom in karo,

95
00:05:50,537 --> 00:05:54,974
aur ab us zoomed-in version ke upper right ko lo, usko expand karo,

96
00:05:54,974 --> 00:05:57,780
aur workspace ke upper right mein daal do.

97
00:05:58,600 --> 00:06:01,661
Finally, ek aur step, phir se 2 ka factor leke zoom in karo,

98
00:06:01,661 --> 00:06:05,131
jo zoomed-in version ke lower right mein hai usko lo, enlarge karo,

99
00:06:05,131 --> 00:06:07,580
aur workspace ke lower right mein place kar do.

100
00:06:08,280 --> 00:06:12,880
Ye chaar corner ek rough idea dete hain ki hum yahan kya banana chahte hain.

101
00:06:13,180 --> 00:06:16,065
Agar aap beech ke gaps ko smoothly fill kar sakein,

102
00:06:16,065 --> 00:06:18,894
toh jab koi is image ke circle ke around dekhega,

103
00:06:18,894 --> 00:06:22,288
toh unko aisa lagega jaise woh zoom in karte jaa rahe hain,

104
00:06:22,288 --> 00:06:26,361
aur yeh zoom hote hote finally image ke ek self-similar part se elegant

105
00:06:26,361 --> 00:06:29,020
tareeke se jud jaayega jo 16 times chhota hai.

106
00:06:29,680 --> 00:06:33,842
Hum bas sab kuch seedha connect karne ki koshish bhi kar sakte hain, kuch is tarah se,

107
00:06:33,842 --> 00:06:37,955
lekin honestly woh utna accha nahi lagta, aur definitely utna smooth ya elegant nahi

108
00:06:37,955 --> 00:06:42,020
hai jitna Escher ne achieve kiya tha, toh abhi bhi hume kaafi kaam karna baaki hai.

109
00:06:42,940 --> 00:06:45,920
Waise jo book mai pichle kuch time se padh raha hu, The Magic of M.C.

110
00:06:46,040 --> 00:06:49,555
Escher, ye mujhe Hahue me ek Escher Museum ki zabardast visit pe mili thi,

111
00:06:49,555 --> 00:06:53,165
jo agar aap kabhi Netherlands jaayein toh mai definitely recommend karunga,

112
00:06:53,165 --> 00:06:55,682
aur jab hum print gallery wale section pe aate hain,

113
00:06:55,682 --> 00:06:59,340
toh ye hume thoda glimpse deta hai ki Escher ka process actual mein tha kya.

114
00:06:59,800 --> 00:07:03,440
Unke liye, doosra step tha ye warped grid banana.

115
00:07:03,940 --> 00:07:06,618
Yahan jo animations hain, unke liye mai us grid ka thoda sa modified

116
00:07:06,618 --> 00:07:10,044
version use karne wala hoon, jo mathematics ke hisaab se thoda easy generate hota hai,

117
00:07:10,044 --> 00:07:11,580
lekin yeh wahi main point dikhata hai.

118
00:07:11,980 --> 00:07:17,214
Unke case me, jo self-similar Drosta image unhone use ki thi uska scaling factor 256 hai,

119
00:07:17,214 --> 00:07:20,154
toh usko jab four corners me distribute karna ho,

120
00:07:20,154 --> 00:07:24,564
toh unke liye har corner se agle corner tak scale karte hue factor four se

121
00:07:24,564 --> 00:07:25,740
scale karna padega.

122
00:07:26,540 --> 00:07:30,410
Aur agar aap unki grid ko dhyan se dekhein, maan lo lower right ka ek square,

123
00:07:30,410 --> 00:07:33,827
toh dekhiye ki jab aap us square ko bound karne wali top aur bottom

124
00:07:33,827 --> 00:07:36,440
lines ko image ke lower left tak follow karte hain,

125
00:07:36,440 --> 00:07:40,360
toh wahi lines ab ek aise square ko gher rahi hain jo ab four times bada hai.

126
00:07:40,720 --> 00:07:43,901
Usi tarah, agar aap kisi chhote square ke left aur right wali

127
00:07:43,901 --> 00:07:47,187
lines ko follow karo aur unko upar le jao, toh woh bhi ek aise

128
00:07:47,187 --> 00:07:50,420
square ke around aa jaati hain jo nicely four times bada hai.

129
00:07:50,860 --> 00:07:54,900
Toh grid basically ek corner se dusre corner tak jo scaling chahiye, woh set karta hai.

130
00:07:55,440 --> 00:07:58,439
Ab humare project mein, jahaan humein sirf har corner se agle

131
00:07:58,439 --> 00:08:02,619
corner tak 2 ka factor scale up karna hai, hum iska ek modified version use karenge,

132
00:08:02,619 --> 00:08:04,340
lekin basic idea bilkul same hoga.

133
00:08:05,660 --> 00:08:08,280
Aap soch rahe honge ki yeh grid aakhir aayi kahan se,

134
00:08:08,280 --> 00:08:12,481
lekin main abhi wo question thoda baad mein lene wala hoon aur seedha step three par

135
00:08:12,481 --> 00:08:16,781
aata hoon, jahan aap is grid ko self-similar Drosta image ke saath use karke Escher ka

136
00:08:16,781 --> 00:08:18,560
final effect create kar sakte hain.

137
00:08:19,200 --> 00:08:24,067
Iska process yeh hai ki pehle aap original image pe ek normal square grid bana lete hain,

138
00:08:24,067 --> 00:08:28,880
aur maan lijiye aap chahte hain ki yeh wala part final version ke iss corner mein aaye.

139
00:08:29,280 --> 00:08:32,987
Jo aap karenge wo yeh hai ki uske andar ke har chhote square ko lenge,

140
00:08:32,987 --> 00:08:37,700
aur uska content copy kar ke warped grid ke corresponding chhote square mein daal denge.

141
00:08:38,100 --> 00:08:42,478
Uske baad, original grid ke har neighboring square ko bhi warped version ke

142
00:08:42,478 --> 00:08:46,098
usi corresponding neighboring square mein le jaana padta hai,

143
00:08:46,098 --> 00:08:51,060
toh aap easily grid ko follow karte hue dekh sakte hain ki image ko kahan jaana hai.

144
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:56,284
Aur yeh jo fact hai ki warped version mein grid lines lower left se upper

145
00:08:56,284 --> 00:09:00,508
left jaate waqt do guna door ho jaati hain, iska matlab hai ki scene ka

146
00:09:00,508 --> 00:09:05,320
scale bhi automatically do guna ho jaata hai jab aap uss line pe upar jaate hain.

147
00:09:06,660 --> 00:09:10,728
Is process ka idea yeh hai ki artist ke liye yeh kaafi straightforward hai

148
00:09:10,728 --> 00:09:15,621
ki ek-ek chhota square leke, uske andar ka content dusre chhote square mein copy kar de,

149
00:09:15,621 --> 00:09:18,700
kyunki itne chhote scale pe cheezein distort nahi hoti.

150
00:09:19,180 --> 00:09:23,625
Ye definitely uss se bahut zyada easy hai jitna ki seedhe blank page pe baith ke,

151
00:09:23,625 --> 00:09:27,740
pura warped final image khud se imagine karke draw karne ki koshish karna.

152
00:09:28,960 --> 00:09:31,947
Toh basically, jab aapke paas yeh warped grid hota hai,

153
00:09:31,947 --> 00:09:36,128
toh har chhote square ko copy karne ka process kaafi automatic ho jaata hai,

154
00:09:36,128 --> 00:09:39,440
aur agar hum iss automatic process ko pura round chala dein,

155
00:09:39,440 --> 00:09:42,427
toh yeh nicely initial position pe wapas aa jaata hai,

156
00:09:42,427 --> 00:09:46,608
aur aisa hone ke liye zaroori hai ki original image mein yeh self-similarity

157
00:09:46,608 --> 00:09:48,780
ho jab aap 16 times zoom in karte hain.

158
00:09:49,380 --> 00:09:52,096
Mujhe lagta hai aap maanenge ki final result kaafi accha hai,

159
00:09:52,096 --> 00:09:55,123
yeh wahi general effect create karta hai, lekin sabse badi baat yeh

160
00:09:55,123 --> 00:09:58,640
hai ki isse Escher ki original composition ki aur zyada value samajh aati hai.

161
00:09:59,080 --> 00:10:03,360
Unhone actually har alag scale pe imagery ka choice bahut soch samajh ke kiya tha.

162
00:10:03,880 --> 00:10:08,491
Quote karte hue, "Maine jaan-boojh ke serial type objects choose kiye,

163
00:10:08,491 --> 00:10:13,300
jaise ki ek wall pe prints ki line, ya kisi town mein houses ke blocks."

164
00:10:13,720 --> 00:10:16,150
Agar cyclic elements nahi hote, toh random viewer

165
00:10:16,150 --> 00:10:18,680
tak meri baat pahunchana aur bhi mushkil ho jaata.

166
00:10:20,060 --> 00:10:23,813
Yeh idea jahan aap ek straight reference image aur ek warped grid lete hain,

167
00:10:23,813 --> 00:10:26,331
aur dono ko use karke ek warped scene banate hain,

168
00:10:26,331 --> 00:10:28,800
yeh graphic design mein kaafi common process hai.

169
00:10:29,100 --> 00:10:32,285
Isko mesh warp kehte hain, aur Escher ne yeh method iss case ke liye invent

170
00:10:32,285 --> 00:10:35,640
nahi kiya tha, yeh unhone pehle bhi kai baar dusre artworks mein use kiya hai.

171
00:10:36,180 --> 00:10:40,003
Hamari story ke liye point yeh hai ki Drasta zoom ko loop mein

172
00:10:40,003 --> 00:10:44,012
convert karne ka pura logic iss grid mein abstract ho jaata hai,

173
00:10:44,012 --> 00:10:48,020
jis se yeh natural question uthta hai ki yeh grid aayi kahan se?

174
00:10:48,180 --> 00:10:49,000
Yeh kaise banate hain?

175
00:10:49,800 --> 00:10:53,462
Aap soch sakte hain ki shuruat me ek simple tareeke se sab kuch

176
00:10:53,462 --> 00:10:57,298
ek kone se dusre kone tak linearly scale karne ki koshish karein,

177
00:10:57,298 --> 00:11:00,960
lekin agar aapne aisa kiya toh turant hi conflict dikh jayega.

178
00:11:01,440 --> 00:11:05,736
Ye dono scaling processes har square pe alag-alag pressure daal rahe hain,

179
00:11:05,736 --> 00:11:10,671
jaise yeh square iss direction mein flare hona chahta hai kyunki right se zoom in ho

180
00:11:10,671 --> 00:11:15,663
raha hai, lekin upar jaate hue zoom out hone par yeh doosri direction mein flare hona

181
00:11:15,663 --> 00:11:16,360
chahta hai.

182
00:11:16,940 --> 00:11:22,280
Escher ko clearly yeh tension solve karne ke liye saari lines ko curve karna pada tha.

183
00:11:23,160 --> 00:11:27,322
Lekin ek aur important constraint bhi tha, jo lagta hai unhone follow kiya,

184
00:11:27,322 --> 00:11:32,206
jisse image transfer process aasaan ho gaya, final result bhi zyada natural lagne laga,

185
00:11:32,206 --> 00:11:36,368
aur jo kisi bhi mathematician ko, jo complex analysis mein interested hai,

186
00:11:36,368 --> 00:11:37,700
turant excite kar dega.

187
00:11:38,020 --> 00:11:43,240
Unke final warped grid me, chote squares waise hi, squares hain.

188
00:11:43,680 --> 00:11:46,560
To be clear, zyadatar mesh warps ke liye yeh sach nahi hai.

189
00:11:46,760 --> 00:11:49,838
Most cases mein, jo warped grid lines aap draw karte hain,

190
00:11:49,838 --> 00:11:53,712
wo zaroori nahi right angles pe cut ho, aur jo chote regions bante hain,

191
00:11:53,712 --> 00:11:56,100
wo generally chote parallelograms hote hain.

192
00:11:56,500 --> 00:12:01,120
